// admissions.dot -- Project Readiness Evaluation
//
// Translates the /admissions mode (115 lines) + gate-criteria.md (195 lines) +
// admissions-advisor agent (58 lines) into a DOT pipeline.
//
// Runs five conversational gates to evaluate whether a project is suitable
// for an autonomous development machine. Each gate uses the reusable
// conversational-gate.dot pattern, injecting gate-specific context.
//
// Gates:
//   Gate 1: DECOMPOSABILITY   -- Can the problem decompose into 100s of independent units?
//   Gate 2: CORRECTNESS       -- Can each unit be verified automatically with fast feedback?
//   Gate 3: ARCHITECTURE      -- Is there enough architectural clarity to prevent drift?
//   Gate 4: TOOLCHAIN         -- Do build and test commands work from a clean state?
//   Gate 5: SPEC QUALITY      -- Can features be specified at machine-consumable quality?
//
// After all 5 gates complete, compile_assessment reads all gate outputs,
// applies scoring rules (below 50% = hard stop, 50-75% = caution, above 75% = proceed),
// writes .dev-machine-assessment.md, and routes via preferred_label.
//
// Verdict routing:
//   proceed   -> done_proceed   (all gates above 75%)
//   caution   -> done_caution   (no gate below 50%, but one or more below 75%)
//   not_ready -> done_not_ready (any gate below 50%)
//
// Node count: 11 (start + gate1-5 + compile_assessment + verdict_gate + 3 terminals)
// Edge count: 11 (8 sequential + 3 verdict conditional)
//
// Source material:
//   amplifier-bundle-dev-machine/modes/admissions.md
//   amplifier-bundle-dev-machine/context/gate-criteria.md
//   amplifier-bundle-dev-machine/agents/admissions-advisor.md

digraph Admissions {
    graph [label="Dev Machine Admissions: Project Readiness Evaluation"]
    rankdir=TB

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Entry point
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    start [shape=Mdiamond, label="Start"]

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Gate 1: DECOMPOSABILITY
    // Source: gate-criteria.md "Gate 1: Decomposability"
    // Question: Can the problem be broken into hundreds of small,
    //   independently implementable and testable units of work?
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    gate1 [
        shape=folder,
        label="Gate 1: Decomposability",
        dot_file="../../patterns/conversational-gate.dot",
        context.gate_topic="GATE 1: DECOMPOSABILITY\n\nCan the problem be broken into hundreds of small, independently implementable and testable units of work?\n\nRate this project's DECOMPOSABILITY on a scale of 0-100. Provide concrete evidence for your score.\n\nAsk the user:\n- Describe the major components/modules of what you're building\n- Can you list 10+ concrete features?\n- How independent are these features from each other?",
        context.gate_criteria="Score 75-100% (High confidence) when: clear module/component boundaries already exist or are obvious; features within modules are independent with minimal cross-cutting concerns; each feature can be specified in under 2 pages; features follow repeating patterns (CRUD, UI components, API endpoints); the user can list 10+ concrete features off the top of their head.\n\nScore 50-74% (Medium confidence) when: modules are identifiable but boundaries are fuzzy; some features have deep cross-module dependencies; the user can describe features but they vary widely in scope; some features require coordinated changes across 3+ modules.\n\nScore 0-49% (Low confidence) when: the problem is a single monolithic algorithm or pipeline; features are deeply interconnected (changing one breaks many); most features require novel design, not pattern application; the user describes the work as 'it all has to come together at once'; fewer than 50 identifiable features.\n\nRemediation: Identify natural boundaries. Consider breaking the problem into a smaller initial scope. Look for the inner loop that can be built first.",
        context.gate_output_path=".ai/gate1_decomposability.md"
    ]

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Gate 2: VERIFIABLE CORRECTNESS
    // Source: gate-criteria.md "Gate 2: Verifiable Correctness with Speed"
    // Question: Can each unit of work be verified automatically with fast feedback?
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    gate2 [
        shape=folder,
        label="Gate 2: Correctness",
        dot_file="../../patterns/conversational-gate.dot",
        context.gate_topic="GATE 2: VERIFIABLE CORRECTNESS\n\nCan each unit of work be verified automatically with fast feedback?\n\nRate this project's VERIFIABLE CORRECTNESS on a scale of 0-100. Provide concrete evidence for your score.\n\nAsk/check:\n- What test framework do you use?\n- How long does your test suite take?\n- Do you have a type checker or linter?",
        context.gate_criteria="Score 75-100% (High confidence) when: established test framework exists for the tech stack; test execution takes seconds (unit) to minutes (integration); type system catches structural errors (TypeScript, Rust, Go, etc.); CI/CD pipeline exists or can be trivially set up; clear definition of correct for each feature type.\n\nScore 50-74% (Medium confidence) when: test framework exists but coverage is minimal; some features have clear correctness criteria, others are subjective; build/test cycle takes 2-5 minutes; type system is present but loosely used.\n\nScore 0-49% (Low confidence) when: no test framework or testing culture; correctness is primarily visual/subjective (design work, creative writing); build/test cycle takes over 10 minutes; no type system and dynamic language with no linting; 'you have to run it and look at it to know if it is right'.\n\nRemediation: Set up a test framework. Add a type checker or linter. Define acceptance criteria templates. Consider if the verification gap can be addressed by a QA machine.",
        context.gate_output_path=".ai/gate2_correctness.md"
    ]

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Gate 3: SUFFICIENT ARCHITECTURE
    // Source: gate-criteria.md "Gate 3: Sufficient Architecture"
    // Question: Is there enough architectural clarity to write a constitution
    //   that prevents drift across hundreds of features?
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    gate3 [
        shape=folder,
        label="Gate 3: Architecture",
        dot_file="../../patterns/conversational-gate.dot",
        context.gate_topic="GATE 3: SUFFICIENT ARCHITECTURE\n\nIs there enough architectural clarity to write a constitution that prevents drift across hundreds of features?\n\nRate this project's ARCHITECTURE QUALITY on a scale of 0-100. Provide concrete evidence for your score.\n\nAsk/check:\n- Do you have an architecture document?\n- Can you describe module boundaries and key interfaces?\n- What are your core technology choices?",
        context.gate_criteria="Score 75-100% (High confidence) when: clear data model exists or can be defined; technology choices are made and rationale is understood; module boundaries are defined with explicit interfaces; key patterns are established (state management, data flow, error handling); the user can explain the system's architecture in 10 minutes.\n\nScore 50-74% (Medium confidence) when: data model exists but has known gaps; some technology choices are tentative; module boundaries are roughly known but interfaces are not formalized; some patterns are established, others are ad hoc; 'we know roughly how it works but have not written it down'.\n\nScore 0-49% (Low confidence) when: no data model -- 'we will figure it out as we go'; technology choices are still being evaluated; no module boundaries -- 'it is all one thing right now'; no established patterns; the user cannot explain the architecture without hand-waving.\n\nRemediation: Run a focused architecture session. You need enough to write a 30-50 page constitution that covers data model, module boundaries, technology choices, and key interfaces. Architecture does NOT need to be exhaustive -- sufficient means enough to prevent drift, not enough to anticipate everything.",
        context.gate_output_path=".ai/gate3_architecture.md"
    ]

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Gate 4: FUNCTIONING TOOLCHAIN
    // Source: gate-criteria.md "Gate 4: Functioning Toolchain"
    // Question: Do the build and test commands work? Can a fresh session run them?
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    gate4 [
        shape=folder,
        label="Gate 4: Toolchain",
        dot_file="../../patterns/conversational-gate.dot",
        context.gate_topic="GATE 4: FUNCTIONING TOOLCHAIN\n\nDo the build and test commands work? Can a fresh session run them?\n\nRate this project's TOOLCHAIN READINESS on a scale of 0-100. Provide concrete evidence for your score.\n\nVerify:\n- Build command runs and succeeds\n- Test command runs and reports results\n- How fast is the cycle?",
        context.gate_criteria="Score 75-100% (High confidence) when: build_command runs and succeeds from a clean state; test_command runs and reports results; commands are fast (under 2 minutes for build, under 5 minutes for full test suite); no manual setup required beyond initial clone; CI/CD is configured or trivially configurable.\n\nScore 50-74% (Medium confidence) when: build command works but is slow (over 5 minutes); test command works but only for some modules; some manual setup required (environment variables, local services); 'it works on my machine' but setup is not documented.\n\nScore 0-49% (Low confidence) when: no build command exists yet; no test command exists yet; setup requires multiple manual steps that are not documented; the project has not been bootstrapped (no package.json, Cargo.toml, etc.); 'we have not set up the project yet'.\n\nRemediation: Bootstrap the project scaffold. This CAN be the machine's first task -- but the toolchain must work before the machine can build features. Set up: package manager, build command, test runner, type checker. Verify they run cleanly.",
        context.gate_output_path=".ai/gate4_toolchain.md"
    ]

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Gate 5: SPEC QUALITY
    // Source: gate-criteria.md "Gate 5: Spec Quality"
    // Question: Can initial feature specs be written at sufficient quality
    //   for machine consumption?
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    gate5 [
        shape=folder,
        label="Gate 5: Spec Quality",
        dot_file="../../patterns/conversational-gate.dot",
        context.gate_topic="GATE 5: SPEC QUALITY\n\nCan initial feature specs be written at sufficient quality for machine consumption?\n\nRate this project's SPEC QUALITY on a scale of 0-100. Provide concrete evidence for your score.\n\nAssess:\n- Do existing specs/PRDs have enough detail?\n- Can a sample feature spec be written?\n- Is there a domain expert available?",
        context.gate_criteria="Score 75-100% (High confidence) when: existing specs (PRDs, user stories) contain concrete details; features can be specified with interfaces, acceptance criteria, edge cases, files to modify; the user has domain knowledge to review specs for accuracy; spec writing follows a repeatable template; a sample spec can be written and reviewed in under 15 minutes.\n\nScore 50-74% (Medium confidence) when: specs exist but are high-level ('add user authentication'); features can be described but acceptance criteria are vague; domain knowledge exists but is not documented; 'we know what we want but have not written it down precisely'.\n\nScore 0-49% (Low confidence) when: no specs exist -- 'we are making it up as we go'; features cannot be described without extensive discussion; no domain expert available to review specs; requirements change frequently and unpredictably; 'we will know it when we see it'.\n\nRemediation: Write 3-5 sample specs using the feature spec template. Have a domain expert review them. If the specs are too vague, the problem may need more product definition before a machine can build it.",
        context.gate_output_path=".ai/gate5_spec.md"
    ]

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Compile Assessment (codergen)
    // Reads all 5 gate outputs, applies scoring rules, writes assessment,
    // and routes via preferred_label (proceed / caution / not_ready).
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    compile_assessment [
        shape=box,
        label="Compile Assessment",
        prompt="You are compiling the final admissions assessment from five gate evaluations.\n\nRead these gate output files:\n- .ai/gate1_decomposability.md (Gate 1: DECOMPOSABILITY)\n- .ai/gate2_correctness.md (Gate 2: VERIFIABLE CORRECTNESS)\n- .ai/gate3_architecture.md (Gate 3: SUFFICIENT ARCHITECTURE)\n- .ai/gate4_toolchain.md (Gate 4: FUNCTIONING TOOLCHAIN)\n- .ai/gate5_spec.md (Gate 5: SPEC QUALITY)\n\nEach gate file contains a 0-100% confidence score and supporting evidence.\n\nApply these scoring rules:\n- Above 75%: PASS -- Confident. Proceed.\n- 50-75%: CAUTION -- Proceed with caution. Flag the risk explicitly.\n- Below 50%: FAIL -- Hard stop. Provide specific remediation guidance.\n\nBe transparent. No rounding up. No optimism bias. A 48% is a 48%.\nIf three or more gates are below 75%, recommend the user address them before proceeding.\n\nWrite the complete assessment to .dev-machine-assessment.md using this format:\n\n# Dev Machine Assessment\n\n**Project:** [name]\n**Date:** [ISO date]\n**Overall Verdict:** PROCEED / PROCEED WITH CAUTION / NOT READY\n\n## Gate Scores\n\n| Gate | Score | Verdict |\n|------|-------|---------|\n| 1. Decomposability | XX% | PASS/CAUTION/FAIL |\n| 2. Verifiable Correctness | XX% | PASS/CAUTION/FAIL |\n| 3. Sufficient Architecture | XX% | PASS/CAUTION/FAIL |\n| 4. Functioning Toolchain | XX% | PASS/CAUTION/FAIL |\n| 5. Spec Quality | XX% | PASS/CAUTION/FAIL |\n\n## Per-Gate Analysis\n\n### Gate 1: Decomposability (XX%)\n[Evidence and reasoning]\n\n### Gate 2: Verifiable Correctness (XX%)\n[Evidence and reasoning]\n\n### Gate 3: Sufficient Architecture (XX%)\n[Evidence and reasoning]\n\n### Gate 4: Functioning Toolchain (XX%)\n[Evidence and reasoning]\n\n### Gate 5: Spec Quality (XX%)\n[Evidence and reasoning]\n\n## Remediation Plan (if any gates below 50%)\n[Specific steps to address failing gates]\n\n## Recommended Next Steps\n[What to do next based on the assessment]\n\nAfter writing the assessment, determine the overall verdict and set preferred_label:\n- Set preferred_label to 'proceed' if all gates score above 75%\n- Set preferred_label to 'caution' if no gate is below 50% but one or more are at or below 75%\n- Set preferred_label to 'not_ready' if any gate scores below 50%\n\nIf the verdict is proceed or caution, include the message: 'Run /machine-design to begin designing your development machine.'"
    ]

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Verdict gate (diamond) -- routes by preferred_label from compile_assessment
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    verdict_gate [shape=diamond, label="Verdict?"]

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Terminal nodes (Msquare)
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    done_proceed   [shape=Msquare, label="PROCEED: Begin machine design"]
    done_caution   [shape=Msquare, label="PROCEED WITH CAUTION: Address risks"]
    done_not_ready [shape=Msquare, label="NOT READY: Remediate gates first"]

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Sequential flow (8-node chain: start -> gate1-5 -> compile -> verdict)
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    start              -> gate1
    gate1              -> gate2
    gate2              -> gate3
    gate3              -> gate4
    gate4              -> gate5
    gate5              -> compile_assessment
    compile_assessment -> verdict_gate

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Verdict routing (3 conditional edges from verdict_gate)
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    verdict_gate -> done_proceed   [label="proceed",   condition="context.preferred_label=proceed"]
    verdict_gate -> done_caution   [label="caution",   condition="context.preferred_label=caution"]
    verdict_gate -> done_not_ready [label="not_ready", condition="context.preferred_label=not_ready"]
}
